{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe two-vote-gate infra epic (1fa8) surfaced a structural gap in completion verification.\nThe verifier (`src/rebar/llm/reviewers/completion_verifier.md`) is a HERMETIC, read-only\nagent: its only tools are repo file tools (over the attested code snapshot) + `show_ticket`\n(over the pinned ticket clone), and it treats all ticket text/comments as UNTRUSTED. It\nanswers \"did we build what the repo shows?\" — well-suited to code deliverables, but it\nCANNOT verify operational/runtime criteria whose evidence lives outside the repo.\n\n1fa8's ACs mixed two kinds of requirement:\n- repo-artifact (add label to project.config, SHA-pin actions, write ADR) → verified fine\n  (S1/S2 passed with signed attestations);\n- operational/runtime (set GitHub repo vars, deploy the image, run the live E2E + record\n  the votes, TEST the back-out) → evidence lives in Gerrit/GitHub/AWS/CI or is ephemeral, so\n  the verifier correctly returned NOT MET. S3-S6 + the epic had to be `--force-close`d\n  (unsigned) despite the work being done + proven live (recorded in\n  infra/runbooks/two-vote-gate-rollback.md C.1).\n\nProse \"it passed, see change 168\" cannot fix this — untrusted by design, else anyone closes\nanything by writing \"done\". The gap: no TRUSTWORTHY channel for operational evidence, and\nthe verifier's tools can't reach where that evidence lives.\n\n## What\n\nName the axis \"where does the DONE evidence live?\" and give each level a trust mechanism,\nso completion verification covers a wider range of work (docs, data pipelines, migrations,\nreleases, ops runbooks) — not just code:\n\n1. **Classify criteria at authoring time** — tag each AC `repo` (verify from snapshot) vs\n   `operator`/`runtime` (needs a signed attestation). Also fixes the source: authors must\n   state, per criterion, HOW \"done\" will be proven.\n2. **Signed operator-attestation evidence channel** — an authorized operator (or an\n   automated collector run at close time with creds) records the runtime proof and\n   HMAC-signs it with the environment key (the SAME primitive as the two-vote / plan-review\n   attestations). The verifier checks the SIGNATURE, not live/mutable state — preserving\n   hermeticity + reproducibility. Incomplete work still fails (no valid attestation).\n3. **Coaching per finding** — add a `remediation` field (plan-review has the precedent) that\n   names the criterion's class + how to produce its evidence, so the loop is closeable.\n   MUST point to verifiable evidence, never \"write a comment saying it passed\" (loophole).\n\n## Scope\n\n- IN: completion_verifier prompt + `completion_verdict` finding schema (add `remediation` +\n  a criterion-class notion); the operator-attestation primitive + verifier signature-check;\n  optional first-party evidence collector; AC-authoring guidance for the two criterion kinds.\n- OUT: giving the verifier broad LIVE tool access to Gerrit/GitHub/AWS (erodes\n  hermeticity/reproducibility, adds secrets/attack-surface, couples closes to external\n  uptime). Scoped read-only first-party facts already reproducible from the repo are the\n  only exception.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Each completion criterion can be classified `repo` vs `operator`/`runtime` (authoring\n      convention + verifier awareness), and the verifier verifies each per its class.\n- [ ] Operator/runtime criteria are satisfiable ONLY by a valid signed evidence attestation\n      (env-key HMAC), verifiable by the completion verifier without live external tools.\n- [ ] `completion_verdict` findings carry a `remediation`/next-move field naming the class +\n      how to produce verifiable evidence; a finding never suggests untrusted-prose evidence.\n- [ ] A ticket whose operational criteria have valid signed evidence closes WITH a signed\n      completion attestation (no `--force-close` needed); one lacking it still fails-closed.\n- [ ] Docs + an ADR record the \"where does DONE evidence live\" model and the trust mechanism\n      per level, with the 1fa8 epic as the worked example."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783033521837460001,"uuid":"cfe01dab-1c85-44e1-8a63-24a057698389"}